view_layer(vgg, test_img_array, 'block5_conv3')

(1, 14, 14, 512)

The beginning layers are retaining the full shape of the dog, although there are several filters that are not activated and are left blank. At that stage, the activations retain almost all of the information present in the initial picture.

As we go deeper in the layers, the activations become increasingly abstract and less visually interpretable. They begin to encode higher-level concepts such as single borders, corners and angles. Higher presentations carry increasingly less information about the visual contents of the image, and increasingly more information related to the class of the image.

vgg = utils.apply_modifications(vgg)

for i in class_index_list:
    img = activation_maximization.visualize_activation(vgg, layer_idx, filter_indices=i, max_iter=500,
    #                                                    tv_weight = 0.,

    draw = ImageDraw.Draw(one)
    draw.text((10, 10), 'bird', (0, 0, 0))

    class_to_stitch.append(one)
In [ ]:
# stich the best 36 filters on aclass_stitiched 8x8 grid
n = math.floor(np.sqrt(len(class_to_stitch)))

# build a black picture with enough space for the 8 x 8 filters of size 128 x 128, with a 5px margin in between
margin = 5
width = n * IMG_SIZE + (n - 1) * margin
height = n * IMG_SIZE + (n - 1) * margin
stitched_classes = np.zeros((width, height, 3))

# fill the picture with our saved filters
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(n):
        img = class_to_stitch[i * n + j]
        width_margin = (IMG_SIZE + margin) * i
        height_margin = (IMG_SIZE + margin) * j
        stitched_classes[
            width_margin: width_margin + IMG_SIZE,
            height_margin: height_margin + IMG_SIZE, :] = img

# save the result to disk
imsave('16_classes_dense_activation_maximization.png', stitched_classes)
